Borrowed from {{bor|en|LL.|oolithus}}; the Latin word was {{coinage|en|Franz Ernst Brückmann|nat=the German|occ=doctor and mineralogist|nocap=1|nocat=1}} (1697–1753) as a translation of {{noncog|de|Rogenstein|t=oolite}} ({{m|de|Rogen|t=fish roe}} + {{m|de|Stein|t=stone}}).<ref>{{cite-book|author=Francisci Ernesti Brückmanni [''i.e.'', {{w|Franz Ernst Brückmann}}]|title=Specimen Physicum Exhibens Historiam Naturalem Oolithi seu Ovariorum Piscium & Concharum in Saxa Mutatorum|location=Helmstedt, Lower Saxony|publisher={{...|Typis}} Salomonis Schnorrii [Salomon Schnorr]|year=1721|oclc=879074621}}.</ref> {{m|la||Oolithus}} is derived from from {{der|en|grc|ᾠόν|t=egg; seed}} (possibly ultimately from {{der|en|ine-pro|*h₂ew-|t=to clothe oneself, dress; to be dressed}}, in the sense of a bird being clothed in feathers) + {{m|grc|λῐ́θος|t=a stone; stone as a substance}} (see further at that entry),<ref>{{R:OED Online|pos=n|id=131609|date=December 2020|nodot=1}}; {{R:Lexico|pos=n}}</ref> analysable as {{confix|en|oo|lith}}.

